We got our drinks and then had to wait nearly an hour for our appetizer to come, which we were told was due to a “computer glitch.” Foie gras app was fine, but after an hour of waiting without service the smaller-than-average portion didn’t come close to hitting the spot. Entrees came about 20 minutes later; mine was cold and my date’s steak came way overcooked. Giving 2 stars because of the attempted bold menu and high end plating, as well as that towards the end our waitress seemed to realize how miserable we were and became overly nice.  However, if you’re charging city prices in Brooklyn and this is the best experience you can provide...stick to take-out.

I always like to start my reviews by prefacing that my experience at each location doesn't reflect that of my party or others that have been to or will attend said restaurant, bar, etc. That being said, my experience at Le Garage was exceptional. The space itself is chic without coming off as pretentious. Cozy, modern, subtle, and inviting (but not obnoxiously inviting) are the words that come to mind when I imagine the location. The hostess was sharp and attentive, and the same can be said for the rest of the staff. Our server was very professional in the way she handled our table. Not pushy, not overly-friendly, and very knowledgeable about the food and drink selections. The food itself was fantastic. Portion sizes were perfect, the balance of rich and light made each bite very satisfying without being overwhelming. Clearly the back of house has a high degree of of both knowledge and practice in regards to French fare as was displayed by their semi-open kitchen which was a nice  touch. Personally I love to watch chefs work. We started with a bottle of the Domaine Jean Baptiste Sénat, Minervois, 2016 as well as the potatoes in duck fat with béarnaise, the smoked fish rillette with trout roe, and the winter endives with pears, roasted walnuts, Bleu d’Auvergne, and breadcrumbs. All of which I can foresee myself ordering again as they were an excellent way to start the meal without being too abrasive on the palette or too heavy in the stomach. Great for eating family style as well. Our main course consisted of the wild mushroom risotto with pecorino and truffle butter plus the gnocchi with country ham, crispy shallots, comte cheese, and truffle butter. Both were fantastic and I'd be remiss is I didn't say that the gnocchi was among the best winter dishes I'd ever eaten. Overall, Le Garage is a top notch French restaurant with plenty of tricks up its sleeves to keep the flavors and atmosphere interesting and evolving. I only with I could thank Rachel and Catherine Allswang personally for putting a smile on my typically dour face.

Le Garage is a really great spot with a nice atmosphere and vibe if you are willing to spend a bit extra for a nicer or celebratory meal.  We came here on a Saturday night and unfortunately it was a bit dead in the place, the bar had people sitting at it, but most of the tables were empty.  Although opening within (i believe) the last 6 months and being a bit off the main street, I don't believe it was empty because of not being well known. I think the prices for this spot in the neighborhood are just a bit too high to have a regular or even solid customer base right here. With main courses around $20-25 and apps $5-10... it really is somewhere that you need to go for a "reason" (celebration, nice date, etc).  With that said though... the food was really really good, and the cocktails were spectacular. The risotto (oddly enough, one of the best priced items at $18) was great and something I will come back for. Although my girlfriend loved her dish (roasted duck), we both didn't feel like it was a $26 dish, but more in the 15-20 range instead.  The neighborhood is obviously changing and so this restaurant might just be jumping the gun a bit.  TL;DR - Food: 5/5 - Cocktails: 5/5 - Service: 5/5 - Atmosphere: 4/5 - ....however, Price: 3/5 maybe
